				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\alpha $$\end{document}-particle decay of the isotope being measured, so that an extremely high signal-to-background ratio is obtained even for highly radioactive samples. For this reason, PPACs can be suitably employed for measuring the fission cross section and fission fragment angular distribution of several actinides, including those with short half-lives.

