The molecular plating technique consists in the cathodic deposition of the source material onto an electrically conductive substrate in an organic solution like isopropanol [169, 175, 176] or isobutanol [177]. This technique is performed in a molecular plating cell designed according to the required dimensions of the substrate and the deposit. A mask is positioned in front of the substrate and determines the spot area. Figure 33 shows a cross section and a picture of the molecular plating cell designed and produced at JRC-Geel. The use of an organic solution minimises the current density during the plating process and minimises the production of H2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
